    "analysis": "We have followed the full workflow: computed global P95 thresholds from full metric series, filtered to the incident window (2024-01-19 02:40:37–03:10:37 UTC), detected anomalies, and inspected traces/logs. Key findings from the Executor results: (1) All five candidate services (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) show nonzero 'error' KPI anomalies beginning at 2024-01-19 02:43:00 UTC, but carts has the largest error_max in the window (0.408609) while others are zero or much smaller (orders 0.008696, others 0). (2) carts also shows the largest socket_max (49.9) with first non-zero socket at 02:43:00 UTC; catalogue/payment/user had sockets but with much smaller maxima (6/5/20). (3) carts shows the largest relative non-'error' KPI spike (latency-90 severity ratio ≈1.17×P95) among services. (4) Traces and textual error logs are absent for the incident window, and aggregated log.error_count is zero for all services, so we cannot use trace call-chains or textual errors to disambiguate. Given the rules: when multiple service-level faults exist but traces are unavailable, select the service with the most significant deviation and earliest/biggest faulty signals. carts meets these criteria (largest error magnitude, largest socket spike, highest relative latency spike, all beginning ~02:43:00 UTC). These concurrent signals (high socket count coincident with application errors and latency spike) point to a socket-related resource failure on carts rather than disk or memory at the service level. Therefore the most likely root cause is the carts service experiencing socket errors (resource/socket exhaustion or socket-related failures) starting at ~2024-01-19 02:43:00 UTC. This explains cascading error KPI anomalies observed across multiple services (downstream failures and increased logs) despite absence of traces/text logs.",
